Musicians, comedians, actors, actors and actresses, some of whom are our supposed role models, are obsessed with sex. A report titled ‘Teenagers and Sex’ published in 2010 in the Ethos magazine of the Catholic Bishops Conference of South Africa, states that young people in South Africa generally do not have a negative attitude towards sexual intercourse; available contraception and abortion are widely available; many more young people have had sex than who are in committed relationships; young gay men and lesbian women face many obstacles and are subjected to a great deal of violence; in the past two years or so, it has become clear that many more young people are sexually active than young people themselves realise; polygamy is common practice in many subcultures; a high proportion of youngsters taking drugs are made aware of the harmful impact of drugs by their peers, not by their parents or teachers; teenagers in South Africa have relatively high rates of satisfaction in their parents and relationships with them; teenagers in South Africa say they get a sense of self-worth or identity from a wide variety of sources, not only from their parents; teenagers’ favourite drug is alcohol; parents in South Africa are less fantasize about disadvantaged, than are the family lives and the sexual attitudes and practices of teenagers.’

Cheers South Africa, and anonymous teenagers. Sex is our life and our death and we literally can’t live without it
